in": 1367, "end": 1371}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:941"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "B7 ligands", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9923213124275208, "span": {"begin": 1375, "end": 1385}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "antigen presenting cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.9135162234306335, "span": {"begin": 1389, "end": 1413}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "APCs", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.796155571937561, "span": {"begin": 1415, "end": 1419}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8837997317314148, "span": {"begin": 1454, "end": 1461}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3553"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8967612385749817, "span": {"begin": 1465, "end": 1469}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4790"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NF-kB", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9573235511779785, "span": {"begin": 1480, "end": 1485}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4790"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NF-kB", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9881186485290527, "span": {"begin": 1536, "end": 1541}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.6425000429153442, "span": {"begin": 1580, "end": 1585}}, {"id": ["CL:0000084"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T cell", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8484414219856262, "span": {"begin": 1598, "end": 1604}}], "text": "NF-kB plays a crucial role in the activation of dendritic cells as well as T cells. In dendritic cells,&nbsp; the activation of the canonical NF-kB pathway in response to pro-inflammatory stimuli, such as cytokines including IL-1a or IL-1b and TLR ligands, stimulate the maturation of dendritic cells with enhanced antigen presenting function.&nbsp; The inhibition of NF-kB suppress antigen presenting function of dendritic cells, resulting in suppression of T cell activation (reviewed by Reinhard et al (Reinhard et al., 2012) and van Delft et al (van Delft, Huitema and Tas, 2015).   In T cells, NF-kB can be activated by several pathways of signal transduction. The engagement of the TCR by major histocompatibility complex (MHC) plus antigen initiates downstream CD3 immunotyrosine activation motif (ITAM) phosphorylation by the Src family kinases, FYN and leukocyte C-terminal src kinase (LCK). Phosphorylated CD3 activates the T cell specific tyrosine kinase, zeta-chain associated protein kinase (ZAP-70), which ultimately trigger calcium release and protein kinase (PK)C activation, respectively. Activation of a specific PKC isoform, PKC&mu;, connects the above described TCR proximal signaling events to distal events that ultimately lead to NF-kB activation. Importantly, PKCm activation is also driven by engagement of the T cell co-stimulatory receptor CD28 by B7 ligands on antigen presenting cells (APCs). In addition, the stimulation of T cells by IL-1 activates NF-kB as already described before. Once in the nucleus, NF-kB governs the transcription of numerous genes involved in T cell survival, proliferation, and effector functions (Paul and Schaefer, 2013).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:14:11 +0000 2026"}